by Aelorean<br>
<br>
<br>
With the introduction of the new EQ User Interface recently, it is now possible to customize the EQ client in a variety of new ways.   Not only is one capable of making extensive customizations of the way things are designed <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  within</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the game, one can also make very radical customizations through the editing of .xml files offline.  <br>
<br>
In this short document, I will outline the basic procedure by which one can utilize UI customizations found online.  This document will not describe how one might edit or create customizations.   <br>
<br>
Also, at the end of this document, I will post a list of links to places where one might download UI customizations and/or further instructions on how to actually <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  create</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> customizations.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Aelorean</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  I.  EQ File/Directory Organization </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
If you explore your EQ installation directory using Windows Explorer, you will find that there are only three subdirectories:<br>
-        help<br>
-        Skins<br>
-        uifiles<br>
<br>
Now, although the word “skins” is being used for these custom user interfaces, that is NOT the directory that contains the configuration files used to modify one’s interface.  The ONLY directory in which we have an interest in this particular endeavor is “uifiles”.<br>
<br>
After opening the subdirectory “uifiles”, you will find that there is only one directory within:  “default”.   This ‘default’ directory contains the default User Interface with which all characters begin.   It is important that you do not overwrite or alter any of the files in this directory!  We will be <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  copying</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> files from that directory to create our custom user interfaces.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>SUMMARY</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
Each directory within the “uifiles” directory contains a complete User Interface.  Therefore, one will want to create a different directory for each complete User Interface one has (ie, one for each character, or one for each persona of a character).<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  II.  Installing a new <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Customization</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The first thing that we want to do is create a directory that will contain the custom user interface.  First, go to your EverQuest Installation Directory using windows explorer and click to enter the “uifiles”.   In that directory, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  CREATE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a new directory and name it whatever you wish (ie, ‘Aelorean’).   Then, click and enter the subdirectory that should already be there called “default”.   Within that directory, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  HIGHLIGHT ALL</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of the files and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  COPY</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.   Finally, go back out and enter your new directory (ie, ‘Aelorean’) and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  PASTE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> all of the files found in the ‘default’ directory.   Your new directory should now be an exact copy of the ‘default’ directory.<br>
<br>
Now, we are free to alter/overwrite any of the files in the new directory created.  If you look at those files you will notice that there is essentially a different .xml file for each of the various components of the User Interface that can be customized.   What you will find is that when you download a custom “hotkey” box, for example, it will REPLACE one of the files that’s in the directory that you created.  This is why that it is important to keep that default directory intact, and then create new directories for your custom interfaces.<br>
<br>
EXAMPLE:<br>
You have been to a website and have downloaded this exciting new “inventory box”.   When you open the .zip file that it comes in, you notice that there is one file inside called <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  EQUI_Inventory</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.   At that point, you just extract or copy that file into your custom user interface directory (overwriting the one that was already there), and that’s it!!<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  III.  Activating your New Interface</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
EverQuest “calles” each of your custom interfaces by the directory name that you created when you created them.  Therefore, if I create a directory called “Aelorean” for my primary character, then EQ considers ‘Aelorean’ to be the name of that particular interface.<br>
<br>
The syntax for changing custom interfaces within EQ is:   <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  /loadskin &lt;name&gt;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
EXAMPLE:    <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  /loadskin Aelorean</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Please note that your new customizations will go into effect instantly; however, it will usually reset all of your windows back to their original locations.<br>
